data.text:
We painted the entire building (all the way around ) of the newly renovated Heitzman Rec Center in North Philly, a hub for the community where folks of all ages can for recreational sports, neighborhood programs, and other activities.

This project was a labor of love with our friends at the Philadelphia Mural Arts Program  https://www.muralarts.org/

Summer 2023

A floor mural we designed for Swedens OpenArt Biennial and painted by the OpenArt team.

You can learn more about what they do right here (best viewed in Chrome or any browser that can translate Swedish).

Winter 2022

A Polytab mural installed on the underpass of a 76 x 20 footbridge.

We really had to plan this mural ahead of time because it was painted on Polytab, a weather-resistant material similar to wallpaper.

Each section was cut into 2' x 2' squares and tiled together to create the full piece. We then painted the pillars to bring the design down and draw viewers in encouraging them to look up.

This project was super hard, but we're so happy with the results!

Fall 2022

Measuring at roughly 500 x 100, this mural is our largest to date, and probably our most tagged mural on Instagram.

Its also one were really, really proud of.

So, if youre ever out in Northern Virginia, youve got to stop by and see this in person! Its HUGE.

Spring 2021

Laminae Wave is a recycled plastic installation we made for the Incidental Monuments exhibition at Goucher College, curated by Alex Ebstein and Amy Boone-McCreesh. Weve been collecting this plastic for several years and this is the second installation we have made with it. All of the plastic in this piece is single-use and would have made its way to a landfill, or a tree, or a fish. This piece is a reflection of our relationship to consumerism and the way that we as a whole are so quick to throw things away without any real concept of where the trash goes.

Photography by Vivian Marie Doering

Reflecting on the rate of our consumption as a society we chose to showcase our excess trash in a transformative and interactive installation. We wanted to recreate the experience of exploring a natural environment but with manufactured material. This installation is made from materials that we have been collecting over the past 5 years as well as things we salvaged while in San Francisco. It is made up of plastic bags, caution tape, paper bags, newspapers, old screens, and latex gloves. The time consuming and repetitive process of layering each piece of material highlights how important our small actions are on a larger scale.

From the outside it looks like a mountain and with a small opening on the floor, viewers can enter it much like a cave. When inside, the exterior light filters through the trash and softly glows as shadows dance on the walls. It is a space of peaceful reflection juxtaposed by the weight of our overconsumption hanging above.

We got the opportunity to hang out at @Starbucks HQ last fall. We tasted SO much coffee and learned all about their blending techniques. The blending process is a lot like creating a piece of art, we mixed different types of coffee together until we came up with a taste that we liked. Then we painted a mural inspired by our experience. We tried to mimic their process through painting, every time our shapes overlapped we mixed a new color of paint. We thought this was like the subtle undertones of the different coffee blends. You can see our art come to life in the limited edition #coffeestories packaging available in stores now #behindthesiren #ad#starbucks
